486:   toggle for all bus cycles even without DRAM access occuring.
487:*/
488:DRAM_MEM_AB.d = !(dram_access_timer_field:[3,4,5]);         /* Same as CAS signal, but the CAS signal is delayed by a second flip flop */
489:DRAM_MEM_AB.ck = CLK_32M;
490:DRAM_MEM_AB.ap = CPU_AS # !CPU_RESET;
491:
492:/*
493:   DRAM_RW is the R/W line to the DRAM memory, and it is a buffered version of the CPU R/W line.  It is held 
494:   in preset by CPU_AS (high means we are not in a bus cycle), CPU_RESET,  and DRAM_REFRESH_RAS.  
495:   The DRAM_REFRESH_RAS makes sure the DRAM_RW line is high (read) during the refresh cycle.  Since it is gated
496:   the DRAM_RW will stay high for about 1/2 clocks after the DRAM_REFRESH_RAS goes high.  That meets the datasheet
497:   requirements that DRAM_RW be high 10ns before and 10ns after DRAM_REFRESH_RAS goes high.
498:*/
499:DRAM_RW.d = CPU_RW;
500:DRAM_RW.ck = CLK_32M;
501:DRAM_RW.ap = CPU_AS # DRAM_REFRESH_RAS # !CPU_RESET;
502:
503:
504:/*
505:   This is the DRAM access state machine - a 3 bit counter.  Reset is held by /AS, so this will start to count
506:   once /AS falls and the next inverted 32MHz clock edge.  It is used to time the driving of the RAS and CAS lines
507:   for normal DRAM access, as well as a 'reset' to the refresh timing state machine used to time the RAS and CAS signals
508:   for refresh.  This state machine is running for all /AS bus cycles, memory or int ack.
509:*/
510:DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER0.d = !DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER0;
511:DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER1.d = DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER0 $ DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER1;
512:DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER2.d = ( DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER2 & !DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER0 )
513:                    # ( DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER2 & !DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER1 )
514:                    # ( !DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER2 & DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER1 & DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER0 );
515:
516:[DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER2..0].ck = !CLK_32M;
517:[DRAM_ACCESS_TIMER2..0].ar = CPU_AS # !CPU_RESET;
518:
519:
520:/*
521:   REFRESH_COUNTER_RESET* is used to reset the refresh signal timing state machine.  This occurs during the middle of 
522:   the /AS cycle.   The reason the refresh signal timing state machine can't just be tied to the opposite of /AS is because
523:   the refresh cycle actually sneaks a bit into the next /AS cycle.  That is part of the reason the inital /RAS assertion
524:   during normal DRAM access is so late.  It could be started earlier, but if it was it would interfere with the minimum 
525:   precharge (delay) between RAS asseertions.   This reset needs to be offset by 1/2 clock cycle so it has two flip flops
526:   offset by a inverted clock.
527:*/
528:
529:REFRESH_COUNTER_RESET_PRE.d = !(dram_access_timer_field:[1,2]);
530:REFRESH_COUNTER_RESET_PRE.ck = CLK_32M;
531:REFRESH_COUNTER_RESET_PRE.ar = !CPU_RESET;
532:REFRESH_COUNTER_RESET.d = REFRESH_COUNTER_RESET_PRE;
533:REFRESH_COUNTER_RESET.ck = !CLK_32M;
534:REFRESH_COUNTER_RESET.ar = !CPU_RESET;
535:
536:
537:/* 
538:   Data Direction Flag for data buffers.  0 = into DRAM (CPU WRITE), 1 = out from DRAM (CPU READ).
539:   NOTE - The DRAM data buffer is always enabled, so it is critical to keep the direction going

