594:   The RAS signal for the refresh cycle is based on the above state machine, and uses one flip flop.  You will notice the
595:   CAS state above is triggered for states 2 and 3, and the RAS for states 3 and 4.  Due to the 1/2 extra offset from the 
596:   CAS flip flops, the actual CAS signal fires at 2.5 to 3.5, and the RAS from 3.0 to 4.0.   This gives the CAS before RAS
597:   a 1/2 clock cycle delay as required by the DRAM
598:*/
599:
600:DRAM_REFRESH_RAS.d = !(refresh_state_timer_field:[3,4]);
601:DRAM_REFRESH_RAS.ck = !CLK_32M;
602:DRAM_REFRESH_RAS.ap = !CPU_RESET;
603:
604:/* 
605:   REFRESH_COMPLETED is an active low signal that indicates the refresh cycle has completed.
606:   This signal resets the REFRESH_REQUESTED_* flip flops.  This is trigger by state 6 of the
607:   refresh signal state machine, which occurs for only a 1/2 cycle period before the state 
608:   machine itself is reset.   I believe this would also work in state 5.
609:*/
610:
611:REFRESH_COMPLETED.d = !(refresh_state_timer_field:[6]);
612:REFRESH_COMPLETED.ck = !CLK_32M;
613:REFRESH_COMPLETED.ap = !CPU_RESET;
614:
615:
616:/*  
617:   These are the combined RAS and CAS signals.  The REFRESH signals are put on all RAS and CAS lines
618:   while the DRAM access ones are only driven based on address bit A1 and the LDS/UDS signals indicating if 
619:   we are reading the upper or lower 8 bits.  
620:*/
621:RAS0 = (DRAM_MEM_RAS # CPU_A1) & DRAM_REFRESH_RAS;
622:RAS2 = (DRAM_MEM_RAS # !CPU_A1) & DRAM_REFRESH_RAS;
623:CAS0 = (DRAM_MEM_CAS # CPU_A1 # CPU_LDS) & DRAM_REFRESH_CAS;
624:CAS1 = (DRAM_MEM_CAS # !CPU_A1 # CPU_LDS) & DRAM_REFRESH_CAS;
625:CAS2 = (DRAM_MEM_CAS # CPU_A1 # CPU_UDS) & DRAM_REFRESH_CAS;
626:CAS3 = (DRAM_MEM_CAS # !CPU_A1 # CPU_UDS) & DRAM_REFRESH_CAS;
627:
628:/* TODO VERIFY - Verify the bus drivers follow this same convention.   I thnk they don't right now. */
